  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "Septum piercings are a type of body modification where a ring or other piece of jewelry is placed through the septum, the cartilage wall between the nostrils. Here is a general overview of the process:\n\n1. **Consultation**: You'll have an initial discussion with a professional piercer to go over any concerns, potential risks, and the type of jewelry you desire. The piercer will also assess your anatomy to ensure it's suitable for a septum piercing.\n\n2. **Preparation**: The piercer will clean the area around your nose thoroughly to reduce the risk of infection. You may be asked to lie down or sit back in a chair.\n\n3. **Marking**: The piercer will then mark the exact spot on your septum where the piercing will go. This is usually done with a surgical pen and checked for alignment and symmetry.\n\n4. **Clamping**: A special tool called a septum clamp may be used to hold the septum steady. It helps ensure that the piercing is done accurately and evenly.\n\n5. **Piercing**: Using a hollow needle, the piercer will create a hole through the septum. This part of the process is usually very quick.\n\n6. **Inserting Jewelry**: Once the piercing is made, the piercer will insert the chosen jewelry. Common types include circular barbells or captive bead rings.\n\n7. **Aftercare**: The piercer will provide instructions on how to care for your new piercing to promote healing and prevent infection. This typically includes cleaning with a saline solution and avoiding any unnecessary touching or twisting of the jewelry.\n\n8. **Healing**: A septum piercing can take anywhere from 6 to 8 weeks to heal, though it varies from person to person. During this time, it\u2019s important to follow aftercare guidelines strictly.\n\nAlways ensure that you are getting your piercing from a professional, experienced piercer in a clean and reputable establishment to minimize the risk of complications.",
